rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description:
A building is a man-made structure designed for shelter or for continuous or periodic occupancy. Note that all buildings are structures.
Things That Are Buildings:
## Residential buildings such as houses, condominiums and dormitories (e.g. Monticello).
## Agricultural buildings such as barns, windmills, and stables (e.g. Boyd's Windmill).
## Commercial buildings such as restaurants, hotels and malls (e.g. The Ivy).
## Educational buildings such as schools, libraries and museums (e.g. National Library of Australia).
## Government buildings such as police stations, courthouses and prisons (e.g. Bastille).
## Industrial buildings such as factories, warehouses and power plants (e.g. Boeing Everett Factory).
## Military buildings such as barracks, forts and castles (e.g. Neuschwanstein Castle).
## Religious buildings such as churches, monasteries and temples (e.g. St Paul's Cathedral).
Things That Are NOT Buildings:
## Building complexes or groups of buildings (e.g. World Financial Center, Marina City). Use the building complex type for these.
## Anything that is mobile such as circus tents.
## Small structures such as doghouses.

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description:
A museum is an institution dedicated to the acquisition, conservation and public display of objects that have scientific, historic or artistic value.
Things that are a Museum:
## Permanent institutions for exhibits (e.g. American Museum of Natural History, National Historical Museum of Brazil, Wonder Works, National Air and Space Museum, ORP B??yskawica).
## Non-commercial galleries (e.g. Roald Dahl Children???s Gallery, Mitchell Gallery of Flight, National Gallery of Art, Lady Lever Art Gallery, National Gallery of Australia) ## Open air and living history museums (e.g. Beamish Museum, Skansen, Doon Heritage Crossroads, Old Sydney Town, Usui Pass Railway Heritage Park).
## Libraries with museums (e.g. Richard Nixon Presidential Library & Birthplace, The Library and Museum of Freemasonry, Ghibli Museum Library, Teleki Library).
## Online and virtual only museums (e.g. Virtual Museum of New France, Virtual Globes Museum, Video Game Museum)
Things that are NOT a Museum:
## For-profit commercial galleries including cafes and restaurants that hang art for sale (e.g. Acquavella Galleries, Alan Cristea Gallery, Park West Gallery).
## Buildings and structures that house museums: (e.g. Getty Center, Main Building, Canal Walk, Palais des Congres de Montreal, PEACH, Aotea Centre, DCU Center).
## Exhibitions and shows (including permanent and travelling exhibits) (e.g. Into the Open Exhibition, Game On, Bodies.. the Exhibition, The Science of Aliens).
## Libraries that are not also museums (e.g. Library of Congress, Glendale Public Library, Glasgow University Library, Biblioteca Nacional de Espana).
## National parks and wildlife reserves (e.g. Patvinsuo National Park, Okapi Wildlife Preserve, Cutervo National Park, Corredor Fronterizo Wildlife Refuge). Use the Protected Site type for these.

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description:
A structure is a large, outdoor and immobile man-made object that is constructed or built. A structure has a fixed location. Buildings, bridges, tunnels, dams, prehistoric structures, tombs and monuments are structures. All buildings are structures, but not all structures are buildings.
Things That Are Structures:
## Buildings such as the Empire State Building and Burj Khalifa.
## Bridges such as the London Bridge and Golden Gate Bridge.
## Tunnels such as the Thames Tunnel and the Seikan Tunnel.
## Dams such as the Three Gorges Dam and the Bhakra Nangal Dam.
## Prehistoric and historic structures such as the Stonehenge and the Great Wall of China.
## Tombs and monuments such as the Tomb of Antipope John XXIII.
## Artworks can be typed as structures as long as they meet the criteria - large, immobile, outdoor man-made object.
Things That Are NOT Structures:
## Animal-built structures such as beaver dams and anthills.
## Mobile items such as cars and airplanes. Use the automobile model type for specific car models.
## Use the aircraft type for airplanes.
## Small items such as road signs and mailboxes.
## Indoor items such as sculptures. Use the artwork type for indoor sculptures.
## Reservoirs that are formed as a result of a construction of a dam, such as the Hetch Hetchy Reservoir. Use the Lake, Body Of Water and Geographical Feature types for these.
## Construction projects that include more than one single and separate structure such as canals, highways, airports or just group of buildings (e.g. Panama Canal, Alaska Highway, John F. Kennedy International Airport, Niels and Mellie Esperson buildings). They can be typed as a project focus.

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Architecture Firm

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Height of structure. For Skyscrapers this should not include antennae or spires. See theskyscraper type
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Structural Height

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the date the structure was last remodeled.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Last Remodel

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the mso:event.agent that maintains the building.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Maintainer

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the type of material(s) used in its construction.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Materials Used

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A virtual property that relates an architectural structure to information about the occupancy of the structure. Note that this covers not only residency of a building, but also the use of a structure for a particular purpose, e.g. a lighthouse for warning ships or the home stadium of a sports team.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Occupancy

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Date that construction of the structure was completed or that the structure was made available for use.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Opened

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Virtual property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the mso:common.operator_relationship containing operation data for the structure.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Operator

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Virtual property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the mso:common.ownership_relationship collecting the ownership data for the structure.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Owner
owner
rdf:Description.mso:type.property.deprecation_info: Use architecture.structure.owned_by instead, as this item will not be supported. DeprecatedBy:[REDMOND\ianiles] Successor:[mso:architecture.structure.owned_by]

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to another mso:architecture.structure of which the first is a part.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Part Of

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates an architectural structure to the engineer who was primarily responsible for the structure.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Principal Engineer

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the designed purpose of the structure.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Purpose

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the status of the structure.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Status

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the mso:architecture.structure_failure relationship that collects data about structural failures for the architecture.structure.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Structural Failure

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating a mso:architecture.structure to its text description of its type.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Schools or styles of architecture that this structure exemplifies
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Architectural Style

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure to the date the structure's framework was completed, usually marked with a builder's rite ceremony in commemoration.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Topped Out

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Relationship collecting the data on an mso:architecture.structure's failure. Failure here is defined as an incident where the structure failed at its intended purpose. For dams, this typically means some kind of breach that leads to the unwanted release of water. For a fortification, a breach may allow an invading army access to the inner city. Failures may or may not lead to disasters, see also mso:event.disaster.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Structural Failure

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure_failure relationship to the mso:event.disaster that follows from the mso:architecture.structure_failure. For example, a dam failure may cause a flood, or a snow bridge may collapse and cause an avalanche.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Causes

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.structure_failure to the cause of the structure's failure. A structural failure is defined as any incident that causes an mso:architecture.structure to fail at its intended purpose.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Cause Type

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all structure purposes. These are the general reasons for the creation of a given structure. For example, a dam's purpose may be flood control, a fortification may have the purpose of protecting its inhabitants. Structures may have more than one purpose.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Purpose

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all architectural styles. These are the general movements of style in architecture in which buildings and structures share common features.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Architectural Style

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Virtual property relating an mso:architecture.style to mso:architecture.structure(s) that exemplify this style.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Examples

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all towers. Towers are the structures whose height is significantly greater than its width.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Tower

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all tower shapes. Entities include conical and skeletal tower.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Tower Shape

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all types of museums. Entities include 'natural history museum' and 'ethnographic museum'.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Type of Museum

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A virtual property relating a standard descriptor for types of museums, e.g. natural history museum, to a museum that exemplifies the type.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Museums

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all unrealized designs. These are the planned structures that are not actually built.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Unrealized Design

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all venues. These are the locations at which some event occurs.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Venue

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: The current maximum number of people that this venue can seat.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Seating Capacity

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: A property that relates a venue to an event that has been held or will be held at the venue.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Event

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.venue to the purpose, the type of use, for the venue.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Purpose

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Primary entity representing the collection of all water towers. These are the elevated structures supporting water tanks. These towers are at sufficient height to pressurize a water supply to distribute the portable water.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Water Tower

rdf:Description.mso:type.object.description: Property relating an mso:architecture.water_tower to the amount of water the tower holds.
rdf:Description.mso:type.object.name: Water Volume
